==English==

===Etymology===
Italian

===Pronunciation===
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-aʊ|-aʊ]]

===Interjection===
'''ciao!'''

# [[hello]], [[hi]] (''especially US''), [[howdy]] (''US'').
# [[bye]], [[goodbye]].

===Usage note===
In UK usage, '''ciao''' is sometimes considered to be somewhat [[pretentious]].

----

==Italian==
===Etymology===
From the [[Venetian]] [[dialect]] pronunciation of ''[[schiavo]]'', (I'm your) [[slave]], pronounced in "s-ciao".<!--provide pronunciation using IPA/SAMPA-->; in other words, the greeting started by saying ''I am your humble slave'', similarly to the Central European greeting of ''[[servus]]''.

===Interjection===
'''ciao!'''

# [[Hello]].
# [[Goodbye]].

